			<h4><a id="comment_link_64119323" name="comment_link_64119323" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23177227&amp;cid=64119323" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64119323)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64119323" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64119323); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Impy+the+Impiuos+Imp">Impy the Impiuos Imp</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Impy+the+Impiuos+Imp">( 442658 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64119323"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64119323"><p>I'm not sure about the Cray 1, but the reason they were so fast was they were pipeline vector computers.</p><p>Where GPUs, then or now, operate math on a single number at a time, these operated on an array of numbers, like an assembly line, doing the same operation in broken up stages.  Hence the time to pop a new finished calculation (like a car) was the time it took for the longest stage.</p><p>That this little whizzing new pocket computer that's nobody's definition of a number cruncher can outperform that 4.5x is quit<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64119323">

</div>
